@gsamal @GeorgeAnanthSoosai @wubo02093104 

I was guessing and testing on what supposed to be the problem. There are 2 instances in which the memory consumption jumps up by a large margin. 

1) The moment I started looping through the array of data I retrieved from the query with forEach and then the usage of sheet.addRow(). 
2) The moment when my code started to hit the writing process `workbook.xlsx.writeFile("ReportDetailProduksi.xlsx")`


I tried testing this with different function, but almost exactly the same usage as the code provided above.
The lowest usage from node.exe normally is around 200MB
The highest usage with node.exe **not releasing** memory after writing excel file was around 1.3-1.5GB

**The first testing phase was:**
_I tried nulling every var and const declared within the code_ 

`workbook.xlsx.writeFile("ReportDetailProduksi.xlsx")
.then(function() { console.log("ReportDetailProduksi file is written."); 
//null every var and const declared within the code including the sheet and workbook itself
}).catch(function(errcatch) { console.log('errcatch', errcatch); });`

In hoping that the garbage collector from nodejs would release the memory, which it didnt and I'm not sure why.

**The second phase was:**
_I tried starting nodejs with the option of `node --expose-gc test.js`
inserted global.gc() into the writing code_
`workbook.xlsx.writeFile("ReportDetailProduksi.xlsx")
.then(function() { console.log("ReportDetailProduksi file is written."); 
//null every var and const declared within the code including the sheet and workbook itself
//call global.gc() to force node garbace collector to start releasing memory
}).catch(function(errcatch) { console.log('errcatch', errcatch); });`

**With the second phase**, the memory gets released although not by a lot.
It decreased from 1.3-1.5GB to around 800MB.
I was expecting it to be around 200MB after calling the global.gc() since that's what I started with

